MBT Atomic Structure Simulation - 
This document contains the latest Python code used to simulate atomic structures based on the Motion = Being Theory (MBT). The code visualizes standing wave behavior and evolving structures in 3D, grounded in MBT dynamics.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# Spatial grid
x = np.linspace(-10, 10, 300)
y = np.linspace(-10, 10, 300)
z = np.linspace(-10, 10, 300)
X, Y, Z = np.meshgrid(x, y, z)

# Radial distance from origin
R = np.sqrt(X**2 + Y**2 + Z**2)

# MBT-based wave function: decaying radial standing wave
psi = np.sin(2 * np.pi * R / 3) * np.exp(-R / 5)

# Normalize
psi_norm = psi / np.max(np.abs(psi))

# Isosurface threshold
threshold = 0.3

# Select surface points
mask = np.abs(psi_norm) > threshold
x_vals, y_vals, z_vals = X[mask], Y[mask], Z[mask]

# Plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.scatter(x_vals, y_vals, z_vals, c=psi_norm[mask], s=1, alpha=0.6)
ax.set_title("MBT Atomic Standing Wave Pattern (3D)")
ax.set_xlabel('X')
ax.set_ylabel('Y')
ax.set_zlabel('Z')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

